    <h2 style="color: rgb(98,99,102); font-weight: bold; text-align: center;">Characterization of Salt Mixtures by Aaron Robison</h2>
    <p style="color: black; margin-left: 30px; margin-right: 30px;">
        &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;As part of Phase I of the NEXT project, salt mixtures of varying composition were characterized according to their melting temperatures (or melting temperature ranges). This characterization was achieved through the use of a differential scanning calorimeter (DSC). The salts characterized in this study include one binary (sodium/potassium nitrate) and two ternary (lithium/sodium/potassium nitrate and lithium/sodium/potassium fluoride, called FLiNaK) salt mixtures. These specific salt mixtures were chosen because of their relatively low melting temperatures (in the case of the nitrate salts) or their relevance in molten salt reactors (FLiNaK).  Briefly, varying amounts of each component in the binary or ternary mixture were weighed and thoroughly mixed before being added to a forty-microliter aluminum crucible, which was then loaded onto the DSC and exposed to a controlled temperature ramp up to and exceeding the melting temperature for the specific salt mixture. Analysis of the resulting scans allows for calculation of the temperature at which the first component melts (the onset melting temperature) as well as the temperature at which the last component melts (indicating that the entire salt mixture is in the liquid state). This information is fundamental for mapping out the phase of the salt mixture as a function of both temperature and composition which in turn allows for prediction of the physical state of a salt mixture of known composition as a function of temperature.
    </p>
    <p style="color: black; margin-left: 30px; margin-right: 30px;">
        &emsp;&emsp;&emsp;Data from the multiple DSC scans for each binary or ternary system was used to construct 2-D (for binary salts) or 3-D (for ternary salts) diagrams indicating the physical state of the salt mixture as a function of both temperature and composition. First and second gradients of these plots were calculated to allow for prediction of expected melting behavior as the components of the salt mixture vary. Below is an example phase diagram indicating the final melting temperature (in degrees C, indicated by color) of the ternary mixture consisting of sodium nitrate, lithium nitrate, and potassium nitrate.
